    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Key Calm Ingredients: What the Science Says</h4>
      <p>The best calm gummies target one or more of the four primary stress-relief pathways. Understanding these mechanisms helps you choose the right product for your specific type of stress.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Ashwagandha (KSM-66)</strong>
          <p>Reduces cortisol by 11-32% over 8-12 weeks. Modulates the HPA axis — the body's central stress response system.<br /><em>Phytotherapy Research, 2022</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>L-Theanine</strong>
          <p>Promotes alpha brain waves within 30-40 minutes. 200mg dose produces calm alertness without sedation.<br /><em>Nutritional Neuroscience, 2020</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Magnesium</strong>
          <p>Essential for 300+ enzymatic reactions. Deficiency in 50% of Americans is correlated with increased anxiety.<br /><em>Nutrients, 2017 — Systematic Review</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>GABA</strong>
          <p>Primary inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain. Supplemental GABA may reduce acute anxiety within 30-60 minutes.<br /><em>BioFactors, 2006</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="info-cards">
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Adaptogen cycling</strong>
          <p>Ashwagandha should be cycled: 8-12 weeks on, 2-4 weeks off. Long-term continuous use may affect thyroid hormone levels in sensitive individuals.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>Magnesium forms matter</strong>
          <p>Glycinate is the best-absorbed and gentlest form. Citrate is effective but can cause GI issues. Oxide has poor absorption and should be avoided for calm purposes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>L-Theanine is dose-specific</strong>
          <p>Clinical benefits are documented at 100-400mg per dose. Below 100mg, effects are subclinical. The amino acid is well-tolerated with no known toxicity ceiling.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
          <strong>GABA controversy</strong>
          <p>Whether oral GABA crosses the blood-brain barrier is debated. Some researchers suggest it works via the enteric nervous system (gut-brain axis) rather than direct brain delivery.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

